  "prompt": "Is Prime Minister of India a constitutional post?",
  "response": "Yes, the Prime Minister of India is a constitutional post. The position of the Prime Minister is established under Article 75 of the Constitution of India. The Prime Minister is the head of the government and plays a crucial role in the functioning and administration of the country. They are appointed by the President of India and are usually the leader of the party that has a majority in the Lok Sabha, the lower house of Parliament. The Prime Minister's powers and duties include leading the executive branch of the government, guiding and coordinating the activities of various ministries, and representing India nationally and internationally.",
